The PF-9 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the 9mm Luger cartridge. It has been developed from our highly successful P-11 and P-3AT pistols with maximum concealability in mind. The PF-9 has a single stack magazine holding 7 rounds. It is one of the lightest and flattest 9 mm ever made. Firing mechanism is Double-Action Only with an automatic hammer block safety. The PF-9 is available in blued, parkerized, and hard chrome finishes. Grips are in black, grey, and olive drab.

TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS
Luger 9 x 19 mm
Weight unloaded: 12.7 oz.
Loaded magazine: 5.5 oz.
Length: 5.85"
Height: 4.3"
Width: 0.88"
Barrel Length: 3.1"
Capacity: 7 + 1
Trigger Pull: 5 lbs.

The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols combined into the flattest and lightest single stack 9mm configuration ever made. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.

The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). The included 7 round rectangular magazine is supplied with a finger extension base plate and numbered holes. The under barrel accessory rail shares the dimensions of the MIL-STD-1913 picatinny rail although there is only one locking notch in the forward position.

I was wondering if anyone in here would be interested in a mag follower that would replace the factory mag follower on the GSG 1911 magazines, making it possible to load 14 rounds in the standard 10 rounders, making it for you to have 14 + 1 rounds in the pistol.

I made a new mag follower that makes it possible to have 14 rounds in the magazines, instead of the factory 10 rounds, you cannot use the protruding metal pin that sticks out of it though, but who cares as the mags are easy to load conventional style.

I understand why they make them all 10 rounders, because of states that cannot have any mags over 10 rounds, but there are states that do allow for high cap mags.

title: For Sale:  FN FiveSeven
postcontent:
Purchased at Bass Pro two years ago. They still carry this model, but they are now marked up over $1100 plus tax. 

I have fired the gun about 200 times, and it performed flawlessly. The bottle-necked 5.7x28 shell cycles smooth and more reliably than a conventional semi-auto round, so I imagine this gun will never jam.

Have original factory case complete with manual, cleaning tools, and 3 factory, 20-round magazines. Yes, they are 20-round mags, and that is a lot of firepower from a handgun basically shooting a necked-down .223 round at about 2000fps.

This weapon system is only familiar to military, SWAT teams, and serious enthusiasts. It is a lot of fun at the range, shoots flat, and kicks about like a .22 Magnum.

Its light, easy to disassemble and clean, and extremely durable. 

I hate to part with it, but am selling due to financial circumstances. 

Will sell for any combination of cash, gold/silver coins, or Uberti/Cimarron Open Top cartridge Revolver (preferably in .44 Special) as partial trade.
